Introduction

In the world of professional sports, data and data analysis is becoming increasingly more important. Statistics are by far the number one tool that scouts, coaches and fans use to analyze sports. Think about the last time that you’ve watched a sports game. I can guarantee that everytime a game is being played, the anouncers will bring up statistics in their commentary in critique of the game. Statistics are used in sports to evaluate players, teams and even the whole entire league! This is especially true in the National Basketball Association (NBA) where teams are increasingly using statistics and data analysis to construct the best team to win and maintain a competitive edge. We assume that the reader is familiar with the sport of basketball. If you don’t know what basketball is however, you can learn more from the link {r} [What is Basketball?] (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basketball). In this tutorial, we will be guiding the user through phases such as; Gathering Data, Tidying Data, Handling missing Data, Exploratory Data Analysis and Statistical Learning. We will be working with NBA season statistics and Individual Player statistics, where we will be analyzing the data to answer the questions;

How does height correlate with player’s passing, rebounding and scoring skills?

Are NBA players scoring more now than before?

By the end of this tutorial, the reader should havr a brief understanding of Data Science and apply the skills learned in this tutorial (Tidying Data, Data Analysis, Statistical Learning) to other data sets that the reader will encounter. I encourage the reader to apply the skills learned in this tutorial on other sports data sets to verify a hypotheses, etc.

Tidying the Data

In this next step, we shall be Tidying the data. By this, we mean that we shall be dealing with common problems that usually come with raw datasets. Usually raw datasets are messy. For example, a lot of values will appear as N/A, Column headers are values instead of variable names and multiple variables may be stored in one column. Below, we shall be combining the 2 seperate data frames we have created above into one dataframe that we can used to perform our analysis.

The first step that we shall do is filter the data in each of the data frames to only include data from the year 2000 and onward. We have chosen 2000 as the starting year of our data because a lot of statistics weren’t measured in the 1990s.The result of this filtering will be a more cohesive dataset.

In addition to this, we shall be peforming string operations on our data set to make the data uniform throughout each of the two data frames. This is necessary because it will make it much easier for us to join the individual data frames in one. Also this important because we want to make the data more readable.

In the code below, we shall be replacing the N/A values with the mean of the data in the corresponding column. In addition to that, we shall be removing columns that will be unnecessary towards our data anlysis. We shall be extracting the Height and Weight columns from the player measurment data frame and the salaries column from the NBAPlayerSalries dataframe. Also ,notice that the height values are not numeric. We will be using string operations to covert these height values into comparable numeric values. After we have performed all of the above operations, we shall perform a inner join operation to put those columns into our IndividualPlayerStats dataframe.

More on Tidy Data

IndividualPlayerStats$blank2 = NULL 
# Get rid of unnecessary column
IndividualPlayerStats <- IndividualPlayerStats %>% filter(Year >= 2000) 
#We filter the data set for Years >= 2000
colnames(IndividualPlayerStats)[2] <- "name"
#We rename the column so we join the data frames later on


PlayerMeasurements$year_start = PlayerMeasurements$year_end = PlayerMeasurements$position = 
  PlayerMeasurements$birth_date = PlayerMeasurements$college = NULL

  mutate(height = (as.numeric(substring(height, 1, 1)) * 12 +  as.numeric(substring(height, 3)))/12.0)
#Use String operations to turn height into a numeric variable

#Join Data Frames
data_Frame <- merge(IndividualPlayerStats, PlayerMeasurements, by = "name")

Handling Missing Data

Now we have all our data inside one single Data Frame! However despite this, there are still some problems with our data. Alot of the columns have missing values. To handle the missing data, we will be replacing “NA” with ther average of the columns.` For example, if a player’s height is N/A, we replace it with the mean of the heights.

#This code replace all missing data with the mean of the corresponding column.

for(i in 10:ncol(data_Frame)){
 data_Frame[is.na(data_Frame[,i]), i] <- mean(data_Frame[,i], na.rm = TRUE)
}

The next step that we shall do is create four new columns: Points Per Game(PPG), Assists per Game(APG) and Rebounds Per Game(RPG). After we have created the new columns, we shall extract the columns necessary for the data anaylsis in this tutorial; name, Year, PPG, APG, RPG and Height.

We shall use the mutate function to create the new columns;

Mutate Function

data_Frame <- data_Frame %>% 
  mutate(PPG = (PTS * 1.0)/G, APG = (AST * 1.0)/G, RPG = ((ORB + DRB) * 1.0)/G) 
#Creates new variables

data_Frame <- data_Frame %>% select("name", "Year", "PPG", "APG", "RPG", "height")
#extracts the columns

Exploratory Data Analysis : Visualization/Summarization

Manut Bol and Muggsy Bogues

In the first step of our data analysis, we shall analyze the distribution of height in the NBA. In order to acheive this, we shall group by height and summarize the frequency of each particular height. Then, we shall plot the frequency of a particular height (Y - Axis) to the height itself (X - Axis). The plot that we will be utilizing to perform this analysis is a scatter plot.

For more on ggPlot and the functions used in this code bit; GGPlot Introduction Summarize_Function Group_By_Function Scatter Plot

data_Frame %>% group_by(height) %>% 
  summarize(frequency = n()) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x = height, y = frequency)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth() + 
  labs(title="Frequency of height in the NBA",
         x = "Height",
         y = "life Frequency")

By observing the plot, we can deduce that the average height in the nba is around 6’7. Lets search up the answer to the average height in the NBA on google and find out how close our analyis is!

Average Height in the NBA

Standardizing Variables

From the plot above, it is apparent that shorter players tend to be better passers. Sometimes, it is necessary to perform data transformations in order to ease both interpretation of data analyses and the application statistical and machine learning models to a dataset.

We shall practice by standardizing the Assists Per Game and Height. What we are essentially doing is scaling the data to a scale where a unit is a standard deviation away from the mean. This method may make the data more understandable to a beginner. To do this, we shall get rid of some of the outliers and standardize Points Per game. In order to implment this, we shall be filtering out scorers who haver averaged more than 12 assists per game. To standardize the assists variable, we shall compute the average, and standard deviation of asstis Per Game, where we shall set the Standardized Variable equal to (APG - Average APG )/Standard Devation APG (and the same thing for height)

For more on standardizing variables; Standardizing Variables

#Standardize Variables
data_Frame_Passing <- data_Frame %>% 
  filter(APG <= 12) %>% 
  mutate(avgAPG = mean(APG), stdDevAPG = sd(APG)) %>% 
  mutate(standardized_APG = (APG - avgAPG)/stdDevAPG)
data_Frame_Passing <- data_Frame_Passing %>% 
  mutate(avgH = mean(height), stdDevH = sd(height)) %>%
  mutate(standardized_H = (height - avgH)/stdDevH)
  

#Plot Data
data_Frame_Passing %>% group_by(standardized_H) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x = standardized_H, y = standardized_APG)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth() + 
  labs(title="Height V.S Standardized Passing",
         x = "Height",
         y = "Standardized Passing")

Height v.s Scoring

We will now analyze the relationship between height vs scoring. We shall analyze this relationship by using violin plots, which show the probability density of the data at different values. We first discretize the height variable by dividing height into 10 seperate intervals, Then create a violin plot for each individual interval.

Violin Plots Discretization

#We break down the height varaible into 10 seperate intervals
data_Frame %>% mutate(heightLevel = cut(height, breaks = 10)) %>% 
  group_by(heightLevel) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x = heightLevel, y = PPG)) + 
  geom_violin() +
  labs(title="Height V.S Scoring(PPG)",
         x = "Height",
         y = "Points Per Game")

This plot shows us the distribution of scoring is relatively similar throughout all the heights with 7 footers being an exception. Looking at the graph, we can’t really say definitively whether there is a relationship between height and scoring. (Later on in this tutorial, we shall learn about determinining the probability of such a relationship).

Height v.s Rebounds

Next we shall plot Height v.s Rebounds! This time, we shall be doing a Box Plot. We shall group the data by height, and then make a box plot of the distributions of rebounding for each height. Similar to what we did with violin plots, we will also be discretizing our height variable.

box_plots

data_Frame %>% mutate(heightLevel = cut(height, breaks = 10)) %>% 
  group_by(heightLevel) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x = heightLevel, y = RPG)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + labs(title="Height V.S Rebounding",
         x = "Height",
         y = "Rebounding")

From this plot, we can tell that Taller players are better rebounders.The Upperquartile and maximums of Rebounding has increase with each height, with the intervals (7.12, 7.35] being an exception where there is a drop off of rebounding. Why do you think this is?

Statistical Learning

Are players scoring more now than players of the past?

In order to answer this question, we shall make group the players in the data set by the year they played, and find the Average scoring of all players within that year. We shall then make a plot demonstrating the relationship between the year and the Average scoring. We shall then attempt to fit a linear regression curve on the plot.

Linear Regression

data_Frame %>% group_by(Year) %>% 
  summarize(AvgPPG = mean(PPG)) %>%
  ggplot(mapping=aes(x = Year, y = AvgPPG)) +
  ggtitle("Average scoring Per Year") + geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method = lm)

Whenever you’re attempting to demonstrate a linear relationship between two variables, one should try to fit a linear regression curve. The curve on the plot above demonstrates that Average scoring has been on an upward trend since 2000. However, how can we determine the chances that the data isn’t a fluke and that there is an actual linear relationship between the variables?

The next question that we shall be addressing is “How can we determine the probability of some sort of linear relationship between two variables?”" The code below constructs a linear regression model between Year and Average PPG.

library(broom) # library necessary to view the model.
shootingAvg_Frame <- data_Frame %>% group_by(Year) %>% 
  summarize(AvgPPG = mean(PPG))


shootingModel <- lm(AvgPPG~Year, data = shootingAvg_Frame)
shootingModel <- shootingModel %>% tidy()
shootingModel
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept) -61.4      20.1        -3.06 0.00754
## 2 Year          0.0344    0.0100      3.44 0.00339

The p-Values are important because we can a linear model to be statistically significant only when both these p-Values are less then the pre-determined statistical significance level, which is usually 0.05. When p Value is less than significance level (< 0.05), we can safely reject the null hypothesis. Since the p-values are less than .05, we can be confident that this model is statistically signifcant and that there is a relationship between Year and the Overall Average scoring for that year.
